  "prompt": "How does a baby survive in the amniotic fluid inside the uterus?",
  "response": "A baby survives in the amniotic fluid inside the uterus through several critical mechanisms:\n\n1. Oxygen and Nutrition\n- The umbilical cord connects the baby to the placenta\n- Oxygen and nutrients from the mother's blood are transferred through the placenta\n- The placenta acts as a life-support system for the developing fetus\n\n2. Breathing\n- Babies do not breathe air in the womb\n- They receive oxygen through the umbilical cord and placenta\n- Lungs are filled with fluid and not used for breathing until birth\n\n3. Protection\n- Amniotic fluid acts as a cushion, protecting the baby from external shocks\n- Fluid helps maintain a consistent temperature\n- Prevents direct physical trauma to the developing fetus\n\n4. Growth and Development\n- Amniotic fluid allows the baby to move and develop muscles\n- Supports bone and muscle development through movement\n- Helps prevent the baby from sticking to the uterine walls\n\n5. Waste Management\n- Baby's waste products are transferred through the umbilical cord to the mother's system\n- Kidneys begin functioning in the later stages of pregnancy\n- Urine becomes part of the amniotic fluid\n\nThese mechanisms ensure the baby's survival and healthy development throughout pregnancy.",
